p98
(lp99
S'earlier, golconda sultanate was located in between the two major sea routes of india, surat and machilipatnam. the town was developed as a trade center and, under the patronage of the qutb shahi rulers, a thriving market particularly of diamonds was developed nearby the golconda fort, the work force involved in the diamond trading was up to 100,00 people. the medieval diamond trade drew travelers from around the world and the ruling patrons constructed facilities and provided security for traders to stay and do business, particularly those travelling from europe and central asia. golconda established itself as a diamond trading center and, until the end of the 19th century, the golconda market was the primary source of the finest and largest diamonds in the world. out of 38 diamond mines of india, 23 were located in the golconda sultanate, making it the \'diamond capital\' of the past. it was considered a point of pride by any ruler to be the owner of one of the golconda diamonds. the top four pink diamonds of the world are from golconda. magnificent diamonds were taken from the mines in the region surrounding golconda, including the daria-i-noor or "sea of light", at 185 carats, the largest and finest diamond of the crown jewels of iran. the golkonda fort used to have a vault where once the famous koh-i-noor and hope diamonds were stored along with other diamonds. jean-baptiste tavernier, renowned french traveller and jeweller dedicates most of the chapters in his book to the diamonds of golconda.'
